equation_narrative.headline: C-terminal position encoding dominates, overriding weak hydrophobic context to select leucine
equation_narrative.story: Position 73 lies in ubiquitin's flexible C-terminal tail (LRGG), just three residues from the terminus. Early layers (1-17) assemble a weakly hydrophobic representation from two structural contacts, but the logit lens shows chaotic fluctuations through polar and charged residues—reflecting the model's uncertainty about this exposed, flexible context. The decisive shift occurs at L24-28 when C-terminal position features activate strongly. By L30-31, MLP neurons encoding terminal hydrophobic preferences (N30:2914, N31:1117) drive leucine from 6% to 88%, achieving 97.8% confidence by L33. The prediction succeeds because the model correctly prioritizes positional context over weak local chemistry.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 show unstable representation character despite reading structural and co-evolutionary information. Two structural contacts provide modest hydrophobic signal, while four co-evolving positions contribute evolutionary constraints. However, the logit lens exhibits extreme volatility: serine leads at L1 (22.6%), followed by rapid oscillations through histidine, alanine, lysine, asparagine, arginine, and back to serine by L14 (28.1%). This chaos reflects the model's struggle to characterize an exposed, flexible C-terminal position with weak local constraints. Early attention features (F1:9146, F1:5480, F1:1508) encode positional information rather than specific chemistry. By L18-23, the representation remains diffuse—leucine holds only 6.4% at L23, while serine dominates at 20.6%—indicating the model has not yet committed to a chemical interpretation.
perception_phase.context_character: Flexible C-terminal tail environment with weak hydrophobic bias from limited structural contacts. The position is three residues from the terminus, exposed to solvent, with minimal burial or secondary structure constraints. Co-evolutionary signal is present but does not strongly constrain chemistry.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: only 2 residues within contact distance, providing weak hydrophobic signal insufficient to stabilize early representation
Co-evolutionary coupling: 4 co-evolving positions detected, but attention heads show low structural/coevol weights (L31:H17 coevol_attn=0.103, L32:H9 coevol_attn=0.579)
C-terminal position encoding: early attention features (F1:9146, F1:5480, F1:1508 all ~44 proj) establish terminal position context that becomes decisive later
Local sequence: HLVLR[L]RGG pattern with flanking arginines and C-terminal glycines provides positional rather than chemical constraints

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes at L24-28 when the model shifts from context assembly to amino acid selection. At L24, velocity events show both attention and MLP pushing away from serine (total_delta=-7.23), while L25 reverses course (total_delta=+4.65 toward leucine). The critical breakthrough occurs at L28 when leucine jumps from 20.4% to 35.3%, driven by MLP neurons recognizing C-terminal hydrophobic requirements. L30-31 deliver the decisive votes: N30:2914 projects 0.951 toward leucine (also favoring lysine and tyrosine, suggesting terminal position specificity), while N31:1117 contributes a massive 1.165 projection. By L31, leucine reaches 88.2%, and final refinement at L32-33 (total MLP proj=+5.11 at L32) pushes confidence to 97.8%.
decision_phase.transition: The L23-25 boundary marks the shift from perception to decision. At L23, the representation remains non-committal (leucine 6.4%, serine 20.6%, total MLP proj=-3.63 indicating active suppression of many candidates). L24 shows the first coordinated decision activity: attention features F24:3457, F24:9530, F24:7941 (all ~10 proj) activate, and MLP total_answer_proj turns positive (+2.73). By L25, amino-acid-specific prediction channels begin firing, though the model briefly explores multiple hydrophobic options (valine, isoleucine) before committing to leucine at L28.

candidates.narrative: Leucine emerges as the clear winner only in the late decision phase despite being the correct answer. It holds just 6.4% at L23, then surges at L28 (35.3%) when MLP neurons encoding C-terminal hydrophobic preferences activate. The decisive push comes at L30-31: N30:2914 (0.951 proj, also strongly favoring K and Y—suggesting terminal position specificity rather than pure hydrophobicity), N30:2884 (0.822 proj), and N31:1117 (1.165 proj, the single strongest writer). SAE features at L30 (F30:3127, F30:7370, F30:3382 with 30.8, 28.5, 27.4 proj) and L33 (F33:1406 with 113.5 proj, F33:8356 with 106.3 proj) represent high-confidence leucine prediction channels. Final probability: 97.8%.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges at L28 (35.3%), dominant by L31 (88.2%), final confidence at L33 (97.8%)
key_evidence: N31:1117 (1.165 proj) — strongest single writer, leucine-specific with secondary votes for methionine and alanine
N30:2914 (0.951 proj) — terminal position feature favoring leucine, lysine, tyrosine
F33:1406 (MLP, 113.5 proj) — final-layer leucine prediction channel
L30-31 MLP layers contribute net +6.25 and -1.79 total_answer_proj, with massive individual neuron contributions

candidates.narrative: Serine dominates the logit lens through much of the perception phase, leading at L1 (22.6%) and again at L14-27 (peaking at 28.1% at L14). This does NOT indicate the model believes the answer is serine—rather, the representation at these layers has character consistent with polar, exposed residues. Serine's prominence reflects the model's accurate reading of the position's surface exposure and flexibility. The representation shifts away from serine at L24-28 as C-terminal position features override general surface chemistry. By L28, serine drops to 20.4% as leucine takes the lead, and serine collapses to near-zero by L33.
candidates.key_layers: Leads L1, L14-27, eliminated by L28
key_evidence: Logit lens shows 28.1% at L14, 20.6% at L23 — reflects polar/exposed representation character, not prediction
L24 velocity: total_delta=-7.23 away from answer, driven by both attention and MLP suppressing serine-like features
N20:48 (-0.312 proj) and N21:76 (-0.327 proj) actively erase serine, voting for S/T/N instead

candidates.narrative: Methionine emerges as the only significant competitor in the late decision phase, peaking at 6.4% at L31 before settling at 1.6% final. Its trajectory (0.5% → 2.4% at L23 → 5.9% at L29 → 6.4% at L31) suggests the model briefly considers it as an alternative C-terminal hydrophobic residue. Methionine receives support from some of the same neurons favoring leucine (N31:1117 votes 0.756 for M vs 1.165 for L; N31:2443 votes 0.399 for M), indicating these neurons encode 'large hydrophobic at C-terminus' rather than leucine-specific features. However, leucine-specific channels ultimately dominate.
candidates.key_layers: Rises L29-31 (2.4% → 6.4%), peaks L31, suppressed by L33
key_evidence: N31:1117 votes 0.756 for methionine (vs 1.165 for leucine) — shared hydrophobic preference
Peak at L31 (6.4%) coincides with leucine's surge, suggesting competition between similar chemistries
Final suppression at L32-33 as leucine-specific features dominate

candidates.narrative: Valine shows the strongest initial logit-lens signal (12.2% at L0), reflecting the embedding's recognition of local hydrophobic context from the HLVLR sequence. However, this early prominence is purely a representation artifact—the model has not yet processed structural or positional information. Valine declines through early layers (1.8% at L8) as the model reads the flexible, exposed context, then briefly resurges at L23 (6.7%) and L29 (5.9%) before being eliminated. The trajectory demonstrates how early logit-lens hydrophobic character does not predict the final decision when positional constraints dominate.
candidates.key_layers: Peaks at L0 (12.2%), suppressed by L8, brief resurgence L23-29, eliminated by L33
key_evidence: L0 embedding: 12.2% reflects local sequence hydrophobicity (HLVLR context)
Rapid decline L0→L8 (12.2% → 1.8%) as model reads exposed, flexible environment
N31:51 (-1.151 proj) strongly erases leucine while voting 1.312 for valine — but this eraser is overwhelmed

candidates.narrative: Glutamine shows an unusual mid-layer spike, peaking at 9.8% at L5 before declining. This transient prominence in the logit lens reflects the model's exploration of polar character during context assembly—glutamine's amide side chain could satisfy both hydrophobic and polar environments. However, as C-terminal position encoding strengthens through L9-18, glutamine is progressively suppressed (8.9% at L17 → 2.3% at L23 → 0.05% final). The trajectory illustrates how the model tests multiple chemical hypotheses during perception before committing to hydrophobic character in the decision phase.
candidates.key_layers: Peaks L5 (9.8%), declines through L17 (8.9%), eliminated by L24
key_evidence: L5 peak (9.8%) during early context assembly — model exploring polar/hydrophobic ambiguity
Progressive suppression L17→L23 (8.9% → 2.3%) as position encoding clarifies requirements
Multiple erasers at L24-26 (N26:1198 votes -0.799 against answer, +0.419 for Q) actively eliminate polar alternatives

turning_points.description: The perception phase shows extreme logit-lens volatility as the model struggles to characterize this flexible C-terminal position. Lead changes occur almost every layer (S→H→L→H→A→K→N→R→A→R→S), reflecting the model's exploration of multiple chemical hypotheses. Key velocity events show the model actively suppressing early hydrophobic signals: L1-2 push away from leucine (total_delta=-2.34, -2.42), driven by MLP neurons that recognize the position's exposure. Attention heads read structural contacts and co-evolutionary information, but the weak signal (only 2 structural contacts) cannot stabilize the representation. By L17, the model has assembled positional context but has not committed to a chemistry—leucine holds just 6.1%.

The critical decision transition occurs here. L24 shows coordinated suppression of serine (total_delta=-7.23, both attention and MLP), marking the model's rejection of polar character. L25 reverses with total_delta=+4.65 toward leucine as MLP neurons begin voting for hydrophobic residues. The decisive moment is L28, where leucine jumps from 20.4% to 35.3% (lead change from S to L). MLP summary shows total_answer_proj=+0.69 at L28, with top writers N28:3086 (0.436 proj for L), N28:1536 (0.342 proj), and N28:1614 (0.295 proj). Attention at L27 briefly destabilizes (total_delta=-3.04, driver=attention), but MLP neurons encoding C-terminal hydrophobic preferences override this hesitation.

Final commitment and confidence refinement. L30 delivers massive MLP support (total_answer_proj=+6.25), with N30:2914 (0.951 proj) and N30:2884 (0.822 proj) providing the strongest votes. These neurons show terminal position specificity—N30:2914 also votes strongly for lysine and tyrosine, suggesting it encodes 'C-terminal residue' rather than pure hydrophobicity. L31 shows complex dynamics: MLP contributes +6.14 via N31:1117 (1.165 proj), but attention erases -9.33 (L32 velocity event), creating net movement. L32-33 refine confidence through SAE features: F33:1406 (113.5 proj), F33:8356 (106.3 proj), F33:5389 (95.9 proj) represent high-confidence leucine prediction channels. Final probability: 97.8%.

deep_dives.label: Position encoding L1-9
deep_dives.caption: Early attention heads establish C-terminal position context. L1 features F1:9146, F1:5480, F1:1508 (all ~44 proj) encode terminal position rather than specific chemistry. L9 features F9:5728 (47.4 proj) and F9:1281 (43.5 proj) continue positional encoding. Note the high projection values despite low leucine probability—these features characterize the position's location in the protein, not its chemistry.

deep_dives.label: Logit lens volatility L1-23
deep_dives.caption: Track the chaotic lead changes through the perception phase. L1-2 show rapid shifts (S→H→L) as the model reads initial context. L15 shows attention-driven movement (total_delta=+2.96, driver=attention) toward leucine, but this is unstable. L20 reverses (total_delta=-2.25) as the model continues exploring. This volatility reflects genuine uncertainty about a flexible, weakly constrained position—not prediction attempts.

deep_dives.label: L23-25 perception→decision shift
deep_dives.caption: L24 marks the transition from context assembly to amino acid selection. Features F24:3457, F24:9530, F24:7941 (10.5, 10.1, 10.0 proj) represent the first coordinated decision-level activity. MLP total_answer_proj turns positive (+2.73) after being strongly negative at L23 (-3.63). Compare the feature projection magnitudes here (~10) to L18 (~7) and L30 (~30)—this is the inflection point.

deep_dives.label: MLP decision layers L28-31
deep_dives.caption: The core decision machinery. L28 begins the leucine surge (N28:3086 votes 0.436). L30 provides massive support (total_answer_proj=+6.25) via terminal position neurons N30:2914 (0.951 proj, also votes K/Y) and N30:2884 (0.822 proj). L31 shows the single strongest writer N31:1117 (1.165 proj) but also strong erasers N31:51 (-1.151, votes for V) and N31:1251 (-0.742, votes for T). The competition between these neurons shapes the final decision.

deep_dives.label: C-terminal position features L30
deep_dives.caption: Examine N30:2914 (0.951 proj) closely—it votes strongly for leucine (0.951), lysine (0.846), and tyrosine (0.836). This pattern indicates the neuron encodes 'C-terminal position preference' rather than leucine-specific chemistry. Similarly, N30:2884 (0.822 proj) votes for leucine and serine, suggesting terminal flexibility. These neurons are why the model succeeds: they correctly prioritize positional context over weak local chemistry.

deep_dives.label: Final prediction channels L33
deep_dives.caption: L33 features represent high-confidence leucine prediction. F33:1406 (113.5 proj), F33:8356 (106.3 proj), F33:5389 (95.9 proj) are the final output channels. These massive projection values (compare to L24's ~10 or L30's ~30) indicate the model has fully committed. The MLP stream at L33 shows total_answer_proj dominated by these features, with minimal competition from other amino acids.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts leucine by prioritizing C-terminal position encoding over weak local chemistry. Early layers (1-23) struggle with this flexible, exposed position—only two structural contacts provide modest hydrophobic signal, and the logit lens shows chaotic oscillations through polar and charged residues. The decisive evidence emerges at L28-31 when MLP neurons encoding terminal position preferences activate: N30:2914 and N31:1117 contribute massive projections (0.951 and 1.165) and show specificity for C-terminal residues (also voting for K, Y) rather than pure hydrophobicity. The model's success demonstrates its ability to learn that positional context—being three residues from the C-terminus—constrains amino acid identity more strongly than local sequence or limited structural contacts. This is a case where abstract positional features override weak chemical signal.
